{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "The inherent nature of large language models can introduce ambiguity or inaccurate provenance [83].",
    "This issue can emerge as the introduction of extraneous information or even noise into the recommendation process.",
    "The large language models may generate responses that, while syntactically correct, lack informative context or relevance.",
    "According to the KoLA [84], a benchmark for evaluating word knowledge of LLMs, even the top-ranked GPT4 just achieves 0.012 in Precision and 0.013 in Recall on the task Named Entity Recognition, which falls far short of the performance (0.712 in Precision and 0.706 in Recall) of the task-specific models PL-Marker [85].",
    "Such a finding suggests that common sense is still far from being sufficiently captured by LLM."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
